[03:43] <chromatic> Infinoid, look at Parrot_mmd_multi_dispatch_from_c_args though.
[03:43] <chromatic> With a signature like PP->I, the INTVAL is a pointer to an INTVAL.
[03:44] <chromatic> See cmp in src/pmc/default.pmc for example.
[03:47] <chromatic> In that case, the pointer *can* be to a stack location, because it's to a prior call.
[03:48] <Infinoid> hmm
[03:48] <Infinoid> that sounds dangerous
[03:48] <chromatic> Parrot_mmd_multi_dispatch_from_c_args(interp,
[03:48] <chromatic> "cmp", "PP->I", SELF, value, &retval);
[03:48] <chromatic> It's an out parameter.
[03:50] <Infinoid> so what's to stop that spot on the stack from being overwritten?
[03:51] <Infinoid> shouldn't it be copied to some more stable location when wrapping a PMC around it?
[03:52] <chromatic> In theory, the PMC shouldn't outlast that call frame.
[03:52] <Infinoid> an "out parameter" is a return value, right?
[03:52] <chromatic> yes.
[03:53] <chromatic> Because the MMD function doesn't know the arity of the function being called, you pass in pointers to locations where it will store the return values.
[03:53] <Infinoid> so you allocate something on the stack and return it, thereby "freeing" your section of the stack... then the caller goes and calls something else that uses a lot of stack... crunch?
[03:53] <chromatic> INTVAL retval;
[03:53] <chromatic> /* Don't multidispatch if you've got two pointers to the same PMC. They
[03:53] <chromatic> * are equal. */
[03:53] <chromatic> if (SELF == value)
[03:53] <chromatic> return 0;
[03:53] <chromatic> Parrot_mmd_multi_dispatch_from_c_args(interp,
[03:53] <chromatic> "cmp", "PP->I", SELF, value, &retval);
[03:53] <chromatic> return retval;
[03:54] <chromatic> retval's a stack variable, so &retval is a pointer to a stack location, but return retval is fine because it returns a value, not a pointer.
